<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="559" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1355,1956]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,310,1427,1452]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559">Material.</emphasis>
Photographs of four specimens (adults), collected on 
<date box="[911,1062,1427,1451]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" value="2009-05-29">
<number box="[911,938,1427,1451]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" value="29.0">29</number>
/May/ 
<quantity box="[1006,1062,1427,1451]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.10286" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" unit="in" value="2009.0">2009</quantity>
</date>
in the city of Diamantina, 
<collectingCountry box="[1360,1431,1427,1452]" name="Brazil" pageId="8" pageNumber="559">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, available at the Museum of Zoology, University of Campinas, 
<collectingCountry box="[846,917,1463,1488]" name="Brazil" pageId="8" pageNumber="559">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, under accession numbers 
<collectionCode box="[1215,1288,1463,1487]" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/9pz2-d68t" name="Museu de Zoologia da Universidade Estadual de Campinas" pageId="8" pageNumber="559">ZUEC</collectionCode>
<collectionCode box="[1294,1353,1463,1487]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559">GCH</collectionCode>
13, 14, 
<number box="[151,179,1499,1524]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" value="15.0">15</number>
and 
<number box="[233,264,1499,1524]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" value="16.0">16</number>
. Six specimens were examined alive with a compound microscope and are no longer extant.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1355,1956]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559">
Elongated body (
<figureCitation box="[396,464,1535,1560]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="10.[151,250,905,927]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,193,878]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1435,193,884]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 8. Heterolepidoderma famaillense. SEM photomicrographs: A) Habitus in lateral view. B) Close-up of lateral region of the trunk, showing the keeled scales. C) Ventrolateral view of head and neck, showing the ciliation and shape of scales. Scale bars: A, 20 Μm; B, 2 Μm; C, 10 Μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/235121/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="559">
Fig. 
<number box="[450,464,1535,1559]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
A). Five-lobed head with two pairs of cephalic cilia. Ocellar granules absent. Dorsal scales overlapping; longitudinal rows of keeled scales parallel to the body (
<figureCitation box="[1009,1077,1571,1596]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1755,1777]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,743,1733]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1435,743,1733]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Heterolepidoderma famaillense. DIC photomicrographs: A) Lateral view of head and neck region. B) Ventral view showing the paired keeled scales at the base of the furca. C) Lateral view of trunk region, showing the distribution and shape of scales (white arrow). D) Lateral view of trunk region, showing the distribution and shape of scales. White arrow indicates dorsal keeled scales and black arrow indicates ventral small interciliary scales. Scale bars: 14 Μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/235120/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="559">
Fig. 
<number box="[1063,1077,1571,1595]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
B–C; 
<number box="[1145,1159,1571,1595]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" value="8.0">8</number>
B). Ventral ciliation as a continuous field of transverse rows covering the entire ventral body surface in the pharyngeal and beginning of the intestinal regions, splitting at the beginning of the intestinal region (U 
<number box="[961,1033,1643,1668]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" value="26.5" valueMax="27.0" valueMin="26.0">26–27</number>
) to form two separate longitudinal bands (
<figureCitation box="[231,298,1679,1704]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="10.[151,250,905,927]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,193,878]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1435,193,884]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 8. Heterolepidoderma famaillense. SEM photomicrographs: A) Habitus in lateral view. B) Close-up of lateral region of the trunk, showing the keeled scales. C) Ventrolateral view of head and neck, showing the ciliation and shape of scales. Scale bars: A, 20 Μm; B, 2 Μm; C, 10 Μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/235121/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="559">
Fig. 
<number box="[284,298,1679,1703]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
C). The interciliary area is covered by elliptical keeled scales, with the pharyngeal portion of the field naked (
<figureCitation box="[233,299,1715,1740]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="10.[151,250,905,927]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,193,878]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1435,193,884]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 8. Heterolepidoderma famaillense. SEM photomicrographs: A) Habitus in lateral view. B) Close-up of lateral region of the trunk, showing the keeled scales. C) Ventrolateral view of head and neck, showing the ciliation and shape of scales. Scale bars: A, 20 Μm; B, 2 Μm; C, 10 Μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/235121/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="559">
Fig. 
<number box="[285,299,1715,1739]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
C). Ventral terminal scales consists of one pair of larger elliptical keeled scales in the rearmost portion of the ventral region (
<figureCitation box="[394,461,1751,1776]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1755,1777]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,743,1733]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1435,743,1733]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Heterolepidoderma famaillense. DIC photomicrographs: A) Lateral view of head and neck region. B) Ventral view showing the paired keeled scales at the base of the furca. C) Lateral view of trunk region, showing the distribution and shape of scales (white arrow). D) Lateral view of trunk region, showing the distribution and shape of scales. White arrow indicates dorsal keeled scales and black arrow indicates ventral small interciliary scales. Scale bars: 14 Μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/235120/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="559">
Fig. 
<number box="[446,461,1751,1775]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
D). Subterminal mouth (
<figureCitation box="[735,802,1751,1776]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1755,1777]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,743,1733]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1435,743,1733]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Heterolepidoderma famaillense. DIC photomicrographs: A) Lateral view of head and neck region. B) Ventral view showing the paired keeled scales at the base of the furca. C) Lateral view of trunk region, showing the distribution and shape of scales (white arrow). D) Lateral view of trunk region, showing the distribution and shape of scales. White arrow indicates dorsal keeled scales and black arrow indicates ventral small interciliary scales. Scale bars: 14 Μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/235120/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="559">
Fig. 
<number box="[787,802,1751,1775]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
A). Pharynx with posterior swellings only.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="559" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1355,1956]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1787,1812]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559">Remarks.</emphasis>
The Brazilian specimens exhibit similar ranges to those of Argentinean specimens (
<tableCitation box="[1264,1337,1787,1812]" captionStart="TABLE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,239,152,175]" captionTargetBox="[159,1403,202,668]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="TABLE 3. Morphometrical features of Heterolepidoderma famaillense. X = mean; N = number of specimens measured." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/ACF1663DFFDFFF7039D1FF4F8B8DBFAE" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" tableUuid="ACF1663DFFDFFF7039D1FF4F8B8DBFAE">
Tab. 
<number box="[1322,1337,1787,1811]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" value="3.0">3</number>
</tableCitation>
), but we were able to find specimens both smaller and larger than those reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Grosso" box="[1020,1297,1823,1848]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" refString="Grosso, L. E. &amp; Drahg, F. (1991) Gastrotricos dulceacuicolas de la provincia de Tucuman IV. Acta Zoologica Lilloana, 40, 47 - 51." type="journal article" year="1991">
Grosso &amp; Drahg (
<number box="[1227,1288,1823,1847]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" value="1991.0">1991</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. In terms of morphology, the specimens in our study agree with the original description of 
<taxonomicName box="[1020,1183,1859,1883]" family="Chaetonotidae" genus="Heterolepidoderma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chaetonotida" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" phylum="Gastrotricha" rank="species" species="famaillense">
<emphasis box="[1020,1183,1859,1883]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="559">H. famaillense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
previously reported in 
<collectingCountry box="[151,265,1895,1920]" name="Argentina" pageId="8" pageNumber="559">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, Tucuman, Famaillá (
<number box="[518,547,1895,1920]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" value="27.0">27</number>
°03′ 
<number box="[591,618,1895,1920]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" value="16.0">16</number>
″S– 
<number box="[661,689,1895,1920]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" value="65.0">65</number>
° 
<number box="[698,728,1895,1920]" pageId="8" pageNumber="559" value="24.0">24</number>
′07″W), particularly in the pattern of ventral cilia, and in the distribution and shape of the dorsal keeled scales.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
